{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "It can be proved that verifying that S ⊂ V is a minimal vertex separator is equivalent to verifying S = Q ∩ Q ′ for some pair of maximal cliques Q, Q ′, that represent vertices in a clique tree of a chordal graph.",
    "Furthermore, the set of minimal vertex separators of the chordal graph is represented in this way in any clique tree.",
    "Other definitions and results on graphs and chordal graphs can be found in [7], [3], and [9].The Laplacian matrix of a graph G = (V, E), where |V | = n, is defined asL(G) = D(G)-A(G), where D(G) = diag(d v 1,..., d vn)is the diagonal degree matrix of the graph's vertices and A(G) is its adjacency matrix.",
    "L(G) is symmetric, so it has n real eigenvalues, and it is also positive semidefinite, so all its eigenvalues are nonnegative.",
    "Furhermore, the matrix L(G) is singular and therefore the smallest eigenvalue is equal to zero."
  ],
